00:00:21.250 --> 00:00:27.650
PROFESSOR: So this first lecture
is a spirited but lighthearted

00:00:27.650 --> 00:00:30.860
introduction into the course.

00:00:30.860 --> 00:00:33.320
I usually never talk about
technicalities first.

00:00:33.320 --> 00:00:36.520
I want to talk about the
excitement of the field first.

00:00:36.520 --> 00:00:39.420
So I will talk about
technicalities a little bit

00:00:39.420 --> 00:00:40.460
later.

00:00:40.460 --> 00:00:44.190
So when you take a
course in AMO physics,

00:00:44.190 --> 00:00:47.450
the obvious question
is, what is AMO physics?

00:00:49.970 --> 00:00:54.870
What defines our field?

00:00:54.870 --> 00:00:59.800
Actually, by far
the best definition

00:00:59.800 --> 00:01:07.650
of what AMO physics is-- it
is what AMO physicists do,

00:01:07.650 --> 00:01:15.420
which is defined by a
community of AMO researchers.

00:01:15.420 --> 00:01:18.460
And this is really
characteristic for our field.

00:01:18.460 --> 00:01:20.660
I will tell you in
the next 10 minutes

00:01:20.660 --> 00:01:24.150
or so about these enormous
dynamics of the field, how

00:01:24.150 --> 00:01:28.500
AMO physics has changed in
a fraction of my lifetime.

00:01:28.500 --> 00:01:33.174
And what happened is, I
felt, whatever I was doing--

00:01:33.174 --> 00:01:35.090
and it turned out to be
very different of what

00:01:35.090 --> 00:01:37.460
I did 10 and 15 and
20 years ago-- has

00:01:37.460 --> 00:01:39.880
stayed in the center
of AMO physics.

00:01:39.880 --> 00:01:41.990
So myself and the
whole community,

00:01:41.990 --> 00:01:45.040
we're moving, and
took the field along.

00:01:45.040 --> 00:01:49.740
So therefore AMO physics is what
gets AMO researchers excited.

00:01:49.740 --> 00:01:50.460
It's not a joke.

00:01:50.460 --> 00:01:53.240
It's the way it
sort of happened.

00:01:53.240 --> 00:01:56.610
Well, a little bit
more mechanically,

00:01:56.610 --> 00:01:59.060
we can define AMO physics.

00:01:59.060 --> 00:02:02.360
AMO physics is what is
made out of the building

00:02:02.360 --> 00:02:05.700
blocks we have in AMO physics.

00:02:05.700 --> 00:02:08.930
So defined by the
building blocks.

00:02:08.930 --> 00:02:16.070
And in AMO physics,
we build systems

00:02:16.070 --> 00:02:24.020
out of atoms, or molecules,
and then photons,

00:02:24.020 --> 00:02:29.460
or light, and in general,
electromagnetic fields--

00:02:29.460 --> 00:02:33.070
electric, magnetic fields,
microwaves and all this.

00:02:33.070 --> 00:02:36.420
So in other words, everything
which is interesting

00:02:36.420 --> 00:02:39.990
and we can put together
with those building blocks,

00:02:39.990 --> 00:02:41.830
this is AMO physics now.

00:02:41.830 --> 00:02:46.210
And this may redefine AMO
physics in the future.

00:02:46.210 --> 00:02:53.740
Now, historically this meant
that those building blocks,

00:02:53.740 --> 00:03:00.830
atoms and molecules, were
available in the gas phase.

00:03:00.830 --> 00:03:03.550
So you had gases of
atoms, gases of molecules,

00:03:03.550 --> 00:03:05.730
and you studied them.

00:03:05.730 --> 00:03:10.720
And almost all of AMO
physics was actually

00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:17.780
about individual particles,
individual atoms,

00:03:17.780 --> 00:03:21.500
individual molecules,
because in the gas phase

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:23.755
at high temperature,
pretty much,

00:03:23.755 --> 00:03:25.840
you learned that in
statistical mechanics

00:03:25.840 --> 00:03:28.040
each particle is by itself.

00:03:28.040 --> 00:03:30.750
And the partition function
of the whole system

00:03:30.750 --> 00:03:32.940
is just factorized into
partition functions

00:03:32.940 --> 00:03:34.860
of the individual particles.

00:03:34.860 --> 00:03:38.780
Well, maybe with some
exception-- occasionally,

00:03:38.780 --> 00:03:40.190
particles collide.

00:03:40.190 --> 00:03:42.950
And the field of
collisions-- collisions

00:03:42.950 --> 00:03:45.520
between atoms and atoms,
atoms and ions, atoms

00:03:45.520 --> 00:03:48.630
and molecules, molecules
and photons-- this

00:03:48.630 --> 00:03:52.900
was widely started
in AMO physics.

00:03:52.900 --> 00:03:59.346
Well, now the field
has really moved away

00:03:59.346 --> 00:04:02.714
from just individual
particles and collisions

00:04:02.714 --> 00:04:03.630
between two particles.

00:04:06.140 --> 00:04:09.970
What is in the center of
attention is few body physics.

00:04:14.040 --> 00:04:17.130
And that of course takes
us to entanglement.

00:04:21.690 --> 00:04:24.000
For instance, people
study entanglement

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:26.430
of eight ions in ion traps.

00:04:26.430 --> 00:04:28.210
And of course this
is deeply related

00:04:28.210 --> 00:04:29.555
to quantum information science.

00:04:32.080 --> 00:04:38.450
Or if you want to go from
few body to many body,

00:04:38.450 --> 00:04:42.230
this is now starting to overlap
with condensed matter physics.

00:04:42.230 --> 00:04:48.650
And this is now widely studied
in the field of [INAUDIBLE]

00:04:48.650 --> 00:04:50.535
atoms and quantum gases.

00:04:55.760 --> 00:05:05.310
Now, when we talk about
many body physics,

00:05:05.310 --> 00:05:11.235
we get, of course, into overlap
with condensed matter physics.

00:05:14.810 --> 00:05:18.010
In condensed, I would
actually say now

00:05:18.010 --> 00:05:21.750
a larger fraction of AMO physics
and condensed matter physics

00:05:21.750 --> 00:05:25.140
overlap strongly, that we
speak the same language,

00:05:25.140 --> 00:05:28.900
we study the same Hamiltonian,
a lot of theorists

00:05:28.900 --> 00:05:33.760
apply the same methods to
topics coming from either field.

00:05:33.760 --> 00:05:38.530
However, often in technology,
how the systems are studied,

00:05:38.530 --> 00:05:41.090
there's a different culture,
different tradition,

00:05:41.090 --> 00:05:43.040
and still two
different communities.

00:05:46.210 --> 00:05:50.410
And the overlap comes
about because there

00:05:50.410 --> 00:05:53.350
are systems in
nature which you can

00:05:53.350 --> 00:06:01.050
say-- they are natural
two or few level systems.

00:06:04.330 --> 00:06:08.260
Of course, we've helped nature
a little bit by engineering.

00:06:08.260 --> 00:06:15.200
Those systems are, for instance,
quantum dots or NV centers

00:06:15.200 --> 00:06:15.810
in diamond.

00:06:26.840 --> 00:06:29.750
Or another overlap with
condensed matter physics

00:06:29.750 --> 00:06:36.030
is that AMO physics is now--
one frontier of AMO physics

00:06:36.030 --> 00:06:40.815
is the optical control of
mechanical oscillators.

00:06:43.330 --> 00:06:49.190
Micro cantilevers, membranes,
tiny mirrors in cavities,

00:06:49.190 --> 00:06:50.610
they have mechanical motion.

00:06:50.610 --> 00:06:52.670
And the mechanical
motion is strongly

00:06:52.670 --> 00:06:55.271
coupled to the photon field.

00:06:55.271 --> 00:06:58.460
Of course, for fundamental
AMO physicists,

00:06:58.460 --> 00:07:01.359
a mechanical oscillator
is nothing else

00:07:01.359 --> 00:07:02.525
than an harmonic oscillator.

00:07:08.260 --> 00:07:13.760
So one can say-- and this
is sort of my third attempt

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:17.780
in defining for you
what AMO physics is--

00:07:17.780 --> 00:07:28.205
AMO physics is almost defining
itself by low energy quantum

00:07:28.205 --> 00:07:30.440
physics.

00:07:30.440 --> 00:07:33.340
So all of the quantum mechanics
which doesn't take place

00:07:33.340 --> 00:07:36.550
at giga and tera electron
volt, which takes place

00:07:36.550 --> 00:07:39.656
at low energy, this
is AMO physics.

00:07:39.656 --> 00:07:42.410
Of course, maybe not all of it.

00:07:42.410 --> 00:07:44.320
Usually when it is in
[INAUDIBLE] solution,

00:07:44.320 --> 00:07:45.930
it's biophysics,
and it's distinctly

00:07:45.930 --> 00:07:47.550
different from AMO physics.

00:07:47.550 --> 00:07:50.730
Or if the solid
state is involved,

00:07:50.730 --> 00:07:52.830
then it's more condensed
matter physics.

00:07:52.830 --> 00:07:55.850
But I would say there is one
part of solid state physics

00:07:55.850 --> 00:07:57.800
which is already becoming
interdisciplinary

00:07:57.800 --> 00:07:59.260
with AMO physics.

00:07:59.260 --> 00:08:06.390
And this is when the
control of the system

00:08:06.390 --> 00:08:09.470
is not done by wires
and carbon probes

00:08:09.470 --> 00:08:12.470
but it is done by lasers.

00:08:12.470 --> 00:08:14.780
So if you have a
solid state system

00:08:14.780 --> 00:08:17.500
and you use all of the
methods you apply to atoms,

00:08:17.500 --> 00:08:19.340
you use
electromagnetically-induced

00:08:19.340 --> 00:08:22.930
transparency, coherence,
all those concepts,

00:08:22.930 --> 00:08:25.410
then AMO physicists
feel at home and they

00:08:25.410 --> 00:08:28.740
don't care if the two level
system or the harmonic

00:08:28.740 --> 00:08:32.760
oscillator is an ion
oscillating in an ion trap

00:08:32.760 --> 00:08:34.419
or whether it's a
small cantilever,

00:08:34.419 --> 00:08:36.010
the methods and
concepts are the same.

00:08:38.590 --> 00:08:42.110
So therefore, one
could say AMO physics

00:08:42.110 --> 00:08:46.580
is sort of the playground
where we can work on extensions

00:08:46.580 --> 00:08:51.940
of simple systems which
we understand and cherish.

00:08:51.940 --> 00:08:55.390
And of course, our
exactly solvable problems

00:08:55.390 --> 00:08:59.847
are the hydrogen atom--
my colleague, Dan Kepner,

00:08:59.847 --> 00:09:01.555
would have said, maybe
the hydrogen atom,

00:09:01.555 --> 00:09:03.055
if you understand
the hydrogen atom,

00:09:03.055 --> 00:09:05.540
you understand all
of atomic physics.

00:09:05.540 --> 00:09:06.950
I'm not so sure.

00:09:06.950 --> 00:09:10.240
I would actually say, in
addition to the hydrogen atom,

00:09:10.240 --> 00:09:12.990
you have to know the
two-level system.

00:09:12.990 --> 00:09:15.370
And of course, you have
to understand the harmonic

00:09:15.370 --> 00:09:16.340
oscillator.

00:09:16.340 --> 00:09:19.340
So these are three
paradigmatic Hamiltonians,

00:09:19.340 --> 00:09:25.870
and a lot of understanding of
much more complicated systems

00:09:25.870 --> 00:09:30.980
really comes from taking the
best features of those three

00:09:30.980 --> 00:09:32.220
systems and combining them.

00:09:35.280 --> 00:09:37.440
If you have questions
or comments,

00:09:37.440 --> 00:09:38.770
this is an interactive class.

00:09:38.770 --> 00:09:41.850
Feel free to speak
out or interrupt me.

00:09:44.570 --> 00:09:51.650
OK so, now we know, or we don't
know, what AMO physics is.

00:09:51.650 --> 00:09:57.255
Let me now address-- how
has AMO physics developed?

00:10:04.200 --> 00:10:07.720
And I mentioned to
you that AMO physics

00:10:07.720 --> 00:10:14.590
has done breathtaking
evolution in my lifetime,

00:10:14.590 --> 00:10:18.000
or even in the shorter
part of my life,

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:20.060
which is my research career.

00:10:20.060 --> 00:10:27.450
Well, traditionally, almost
all fields in science

00:10:27.450 --> 00:10:30.780
started with observing nature.

00:10:33.740 --> 00:10:37.740
The pursuit of science was
born out of human curiosity

00:10:37.740 --> 00:10:40.350
to understand the
world around us.

00:10:40.350 --> 00:10:43.090
And atomic
physicists, well, they

00:10:43.090 --> 00:10:48.330
started to observe atoms and
molecules, usually in the gas

00:10:48.330 --> 00:10:51.390
phase, and what they were doing.

00:10:51.390 --> 00:10:58.520
And already there
was some evolution,

00:10:58.520 --> 00:11:02.780
because original observations
at low resolution

00:11:02.780 --> 00:11:07.740
were taken to a
completely new level when

00:11:07.740 --> 00:11:12.360
high-resolution methods were
developed, when lasers came

00:11:12.360 --> 00:11:15.480
along, when people had light
sources which had fantastic

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:20.500
resolution and eventually
finer and finer details

00:11:20.500 --> 00:11:25.100
of the structure of atoms and
interactions between atoms

00:11:25.100 --> 00:11:27.980
were resolved.

00:11:27.980 --> 00:11:31.780
But AMO physics is
a field which has

00:11:31.780 --> 00:11:35.640
taken the pursuit of
science much further.

00:11:35.640 --> 00:11:39.110
So there is not just
observation of nature--

00:11:39.110 --> 00:11:41.930
and I want to write that
with capital letters--

00:11:41.930 --> 00:11:43.475
there is CONTROL OF NATURE.

00:11:46.380 --> 00:11:48.500
And you maybe take
it for granted,

00:11:48.500 --> 00:11:50.200
but you should
really appreciate it,

00:11:50.200 --> 00:11:54.850
that controlling nature, having
control over what you study,

00:11:54.850 --> 00:11:58.130
modify it, advance it,
take it to the next level,

00:11:58.130 --> 00:12:00.650
is really something wonderful.

00:12:00.650 --> 00:12:03.190
It is completely absent
in certain fields,

00:12:03.190 --> 00:12:04.180
like astrophysics.

00:12:04.180 --> 00:12:07.880
In astrophysics, all you
can do is, you can observe.

00:12:07.880 --> 00:12:12.700
In atomic physics, we create
the objects we can observe.

00:12:12.700 --> 00:12:20.200
So the control of nature, the
control of our atomic physics

00:12:20.200 --> 00:12:22.750
system, developed in stages.

00:12:26.230 --> 00:12:31.980
The first kind of control was
exerted about internal states.

00:12:31.980 --> 00:12:35.810
If you have an atom
at thermal energies,

00:12:35.810 --> 00:12:38.380
it would only come in
hyperfine states which

00:12:38.380 --> 00:12:40.390
are thermally
populated, or molecules

00:12:40.390 --> 00:12:44.640
come in rotation states, and
well your limited control

00:12:44.640 --> 00:12:47.390
was simply to raise and
lower the temperature.

00:12:47.390 --> 00:12:51.520
But with the advent of optical
pumping-- this actually

00:12:51.520 --> 00:12:55.010
happened already with
classical light sources

00:12:55.010 --> 00:12:57.440
before the invention
of the laser-- so

00:12:57.440 --> 00:13:02.790
with optical pumping, you can
pump the internal population

00:13:02.790 --> 00:13:06.690
of molecules into, let's say,
a single rotational state.

00:13:06.690 --> 00:13:11.210
So this is control over
the internal Hilbert space.

00:13:11.210 --> 00:13:16.360
And this was actually
rewarded with a Nobel Prize

00:13:16.360 --> 00:13:21.630
to Alfred Kastler in 1966.

00:13:21.630 --> 00:13:24.390
Of course, the next
step after controlling

00:13:24.390 --> 00:13:26.950
the internal degrees
of freedom is

00:13:26.950 --> 00:13:30.600
have control over the
external degrees of freedom,

00:13:30.600 --> 00:13:33.415
and this means control motion.

00:13:37.590 --> 00:13:40.800
This was of course
pursued by understanding

00:13:40.800 --> 00:13:43.250
the mechanical aspect of light.

00:13:43.250 --> 00:13:48.120
How do photons mechanically
interact with atoms?

00:13:48.120 --> 00:13:50.740
This eventually led
to laser cooling

00:13:50.740 --> 00:13:53.270
and Bose-Einstein condensation.

00:13:53.270 --> 00:14:02.230
And those developments were
recognized with major prizes.

00:14:02.230 --> 00:14:04.730
Well there is more to
it than controlling

00:14:04.730 --> 00:14:09.150
internal and external
degrees of freedom.

00:14:09.150 --> 00:14:13.560
You can then also say,
well, how much can we

00:14:13.560 --> 00:14:16.890
control the number
of building blocks?

00:14:16.890 --> 00:14:21.490
And eventually AMO
physics advanced

00:14:21.490 --> 00:14:25.180
to exert control
onto single quantum

00:14:25.180 --> 00:14:31.740
systems-- single
photons, single atoms.

00:14:31.740 --> 00:14:35.070
A single atom in a cavity
exchanging a photon

00:14:35.070 --> 00:14:38.980
with a cavity
thousands of times.

00:14:38.980 --> 00:14:42.510
So this control of
single quantum systems

00:14:42.510 --> 00:14:46.280
was actually just recognized
with a Nobel Prize

00:14:46.280 --> 00:14:49.020
a few months ago.

00:14:49.020 --> 00:14:53.590
Well, at this point I
sometimes make the joke,

00:14:53.590 --> 00:15:03.130
we have gone from big ensembles
in many, many quantum states

00:15:03.130 --> 00:15:09.040
to single photons, single atoms,
in a single quantum state--

00:15:09.040 --> 00:15:10.810
a single quantum state
for many particles

00:15:10.810 --> 00:15:14.250
is Bose-Einstein condensation.

00:15:14.250 --> 00:15:18.770
So we have really gone down to
single atoms, single photons,

00:15:18.770 --> 00:15:20.550
single quantum states.

00:15:20.550 --> 00:15:23.260
Well, what comes next?

00:15:23.260 --> 00:15:27.090
To have no atoms and
no light in vacuum.

00:15:27.090 --> 00:15:30.180
Well, the vacuum has some
very interesting properties.

00:15:30.180 --> 00:15:32.520
And if you talk
to Frank Wilczek,

00:15:32.520 --> 00:15:36.210
the nature of the
vacuum and dark energy

00:15:36.210 --> 00:15:40.180
is one of the big mysteries
in physics and in science

00:15:40.180 --> 00:15:41.080
in general.

00:15:41.080 --> 00:15:44.550
But the study of
that is definitely

00:15:44.550 --> 00:15:47.850
outside the scope
of AMO physics.

00:15:47.850 --> 00:15:51.370
So what happens is, when we
have gone down and have now

00:15:51.370 --> 00:15:54.370
control over the
building blocks,

00:15:54.370 --> 00:15:57.840
now we can sort of go up
again in a controlled way,

00:15:57.840 --> 00:16:02.130
create complexity by
assembling a few photons,

00:16:02.130 --> 00:16:07.080
a few atoms into new
entangled states,

00:16:07.080 --> 00:16:11.670
so we can now take our system
into very different regions

00:16:11.670 --> 00:16:13.790
of Hilbert space.

00:16:13.790 --> 00:16:18.930
So what is defining
now the control is,

00:16:18.930 --> 00:16:22.180
we want to use this pristine
control over the building

00:16:22.180 --> 00:16:27.500
blocks to now put in something
which hasn't existed naturally

00:16:27.500 --> 00:16:32.520
before, or when it existed
it was completely obscured,

00:16:32.520 --> 00:16:39.296
completely hidden by
thermal motion or by you

00:16:39.296 --> 00:16:43.110
can say homogenous broadening
our lack of control.

00:16:43.110 --> 00:16:45.080
And the best
buzzwords are here now

00:16:45.080 --> 00:16:49.330
entanglement and
many-body physics.

00:16:52.150 --> 00:16:59.176
It's hard to capture that as in
a diagram, but let me try that.

00:16:59.176 --> 00:17:00.800
I don't know actually
what I'm drawing,

00:17:00.800 --> 00:17:03.050
but I think you get
the message that this

00:17:03.050 --> 00:17:05.579
is sort of Hilbert space.

00:17:05.579 --> 00:17:09.040
And I have 2 x's.

00:17:09.040 --> 00:17:14.569
One is sort of entropy,
high temperature,

00:17:14.569 --> 00:17:18.869
and the other one is complexity.

00:17:18.869 --> 00:17:25.060
And for quite awhile,
people studied hot gases.

00:17:25.060 --> 00:17:28.569
So these are gases, there's
a lot of entropy in it.

00:17:28.569 --> 00:17:32.480
The complexity is actually
not particularly high.

00:17:32.480 --> 00:17:38.470
And everything is described
by a statistical operator--

00:17:38.470 --> 00:17:39.285
the density matrix.

00:17:42.810 --> 00:17:46.710
The pursuit of
cooling, and actually,

00:17:46.710 --> 00:17:50.680
control-- gaining
information about a system

00:17:50.680 --> 00:17:51.910
is also a way of cooling.

00:17:51.910 --> 00:17:54.140
If you know in which
state the atom is,

00:17:54.140 --> 00:17:56.110
the entropy of
the system is zero

00:17:56.110 --> 00:17:58.670
even if you haven't changed
the state of the atom.

00:17:58.670 --> 00:18:06.650
So control and cooling, control
measurement and cooling,

00:18:06.650 --> 00:18:09.730
has now taken us
to the point where

00:18:09.730 --> 00:18:12.190
we have systems which
have no entropy anymore.

00:18:12.190 --> 00:18:15.690
They are very,
very well defined.

00:18:15.690 --> 00:18:21.390
And our goal now is
to take these systems

00:18:21.390 --> 00:18:26.440
to much more complexity where
wave functions become entangled

00:18:26.440 --> 00:18:30.270
and we have strong correlations
in many-body systems.

00:18:30.270 --> 00:18:34.880
But this is now,
maybe here, this

00:18:34.880 --> 00:18:37.650
is now described
by wave functions.

00:18:37.650 --> 00:18:42.290
But here is the wave function
of a single particle,

00:18:42.290 --> 00:18:48.459
and here we have highly
correlated, highly entangled

00:18:48.459 --> 00:18:49.500
many-body wave functions.

00:18:53.320 --> 00:18:58.120
So at least for me--
but all predictions

00:18:58.120 --> 00:19:00.440
are notoriously
incorrect when you

00:19:00.440 --> 00:19:02.560
look at them in a
few years from now--

00:19:02.560 --> 00:19:06.360
but for me, this is where
the future of our field

00:19:06.360 --> 00:19:11.570
is moving, to get into
interesting regions of Hilbert

00:19:11.570 --> 00:19:14.655
space where no person
has been before.

00:19:20.090 --> 00:19:25.880
As an experimentalist, and with
a lot of experimental graduate

00:19:25.880 --> 00:19:30.540
students in this room,
I want to emphasize

00:19:30.540 --> 00:19:35.650
that a lot of those rapid
developments of the field

00:19:35.650 --> 00:19:36.925
are driven by technology.

00:19:41.190 --> 00:19:44.235
So it's driven by
technology advances.

00:19:49.570 --> 00:19:51.900
In the '50s and
early '60s, people

00:19:51.900 --> 00:19:56.380
thought AMO physics
is pretty much dead.

00:19:56.380 --> 00:20:01.040
Only a few people with gray hair
continue what they have done

00:20:01.040 --> 00:20:03.850
and the field will
eventually die.

00:20:03.850 --> 00:20:10.750
But then technological
developments

00:20:10.750 --> 00:20:14.370
made it possible to do
major conceptual advances.

00:20:14.370 --> 00:20:16.910
I've mentioned the conceptual
advances-- let me now

00:20:16.910 --> 00:20:21.550
say a few words about the
technology which has driven it.

00:20:21.550 --> 00:20:26.200
There was one phase of
developing lasers which

00:20:26.200 --> 00:20:28.310
I experienced when
I was a student.

00:20:28.310 --> 00:20:30.630
But those lasers were fantastic.

00:20:30.630 --> 00:20:33.720
They were very narrow
already, very stable,

00:20:33.720 --> 00:20:37.260
but they were very expensive
and very complicated.

00:20:37.260 --> 00:20:40.850
So if you had one laser,
this defined your laboratory

00:20:40.850 --> 00:20:42.420
and then you studied
a lot of things

00:20:42.420 --> 00:20:45.800
with the single laser
you could afford.

00:20:45.800 --> 00:20:50.740
Well, you're probably
not used to one big dye

00:20:50.740 --> 00:20:53.540
laser pumped with a
big argon ion laser.

00:20:53.540 --> 00:20:57.230
It was a $250,000
investment for the lab.

00:20:57.230 --> 00:21:01.000
And of course, you couldn't
afford a second laser.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:06.270
It required 50 kilowatts
pf electrical power.

00:21:06.270 --> 00:21:08.620
And all this power
had to be cooled away

00:21:08.620 --> 00:21:11.620
by gushing water
through thick pipes.

00:21:11.620 --> 00:21:13.720
So it was an
expensive undertaking

00:21:13.720 --> 00:21:18.680
but you could really do
wonderful science with it.

00:21:18.680 --> 00:21:21.010
So what I've seen
in the last 20 years

00:21:21.010 --> 00:21:25.670
is the proliferation
of solid state lasers,

00:21:25.670 --> 00:21:29.930
starting with diode
lasers and continuing

00:21:29.930 --> 00:21:32.140
until the present year.

00:21:32.140 --> 00:21:35.530
So now, in a lot of our
laboratories here at MIT,

00:21:35.530 --> 00:21:36.350
we have 10 lasers.

00:21:36.350 --> 00:21:38.990
And we've stopped counting
them, because adding a laser

00:21:38.990 --> 00:21:41.340
to the system is
almost like adding

00:21:41.340 --> 00:21:48.130
an amplifier to a circuit
or adding another circuit

00:21:48.130 --> 00:21:51.510
to a data acquisition system.

00:21:51.510 --> 00:21:56.360
But it's not just the
simplicity of the lasers

00:21:56.360 --> 00:21:58.080
which we have now,
the robustness--

00:21:58.080 --> 00:22:00.770
to have 10 lasers in
the lab, it's fine.

00:22:00.770 --> 00:22:02.990
Previously, if you had
three lasers in the lab,

00:22:02.990 --> 00:22:06.240
you spent 90% of your time just
keeping the lasers running.

00:22:06.240 --> 00:22:11.190
Those lasers, not so much
continuous-wave lasers,

00:22:11.190 --> 00:22:15.840
but pulse lasers have also
very, very different properties.

00:22:15.840 --> 00:22:24.520
Laser pulses got very,
very short-- femtosecond

00:22:24.520 --> 00:22:27.280
or even attosecond.

00:22:27.280 --> 00:22:33.720
Shorter pulses means
that the energy is now

00:22:33.720 --> 00:22:37.570
focused to a much
shorter temporal window.

00:22:37.570 --> 00:22:41.360
Therefore, laser pulses of
very, very high intensity--

00:22:41.360 --> 00:22:45.250
if you focus a short pulse
laser on an atomic system,

00:22:45.250 --> 00:22:48.600
you can easily reach
an electric field

00:22:48.600 --> 00:22:51.985
of the laser which is stronger
than the electric field

00:22:51.985 --> 00:22:53.240
of the atom.

00:22:53.240 --> 00:22:56.490
So in other words, if you have
protons and electrons-- well,

00:22:56.490 --> 00:22:59.290
maybe the outer electrons, not
get down to the single protons.

00:22:59.290 --> 00:23:03.200
But maybe an ionic core,
and you've electrons.

00:23:03.200 --> 00:23:06.590
Now, you should first look at
the motion of free electrons

00:23:06.590 --> 00:23:09.981
in the strong field of the laser
and add the atomic structure

00:23:09.981 --> 00:23:10.730
as a perturbation.

00:23:10.730 --> 00:23:17.520
It really takes the hierarchy
of effects upside down.

00:23:17.520 --> 00:23:23.960
So the appearance of
high intensity lasers

00:23:23.960 --> 00:23:28.560
has given rise to a whole
new field of atomic physics.

00:23:28.560 --> 00:23:30.190
Lasers got more precise.

00:23:33.450 --> 00:23:37.660
The invention of
the frequency combs,

00:23:37.660 --> 00:23:40.700
recognized by the
Nobel Prize in 2005,

00:23:40.700 --> 00:23:48.070
meant now that we can
control laser frequencies

00:23:48.070 --> 00:23:51.700
at a level of 10
to the minus 17.

00:23:51.700 --> 00:23:59.880
And this has completely
redefined precision metrology

00:23:59.880 --> 00:24:05.974
and has advanced the control
over atoms and molecules

00:24:05.974 --> 00:24:06.890
I've mentioned before.

00:24:10.640 --> 00:24:14.220
Finally, another
technical development

00:24:14.220 --> 00:24:19.260
which plays a major role in
research being pursued here

00:24:19.260 --> 00:24:22.530
at MIT and elsewhere
are the development

00:24:22.530 --> 00:24:25.440
of high finesse cavities.

00:24:25.440 --> 00:24:28.005
High finesse cavities
in the microwave range--

00:24:28.005 --> 00:24:30.240
then they're
superconducting-- or high

00:24:30.240 --> 00:24:34.670
finesse optical cavities
by having super mirrors.

00:24:34.670 --> 00:24:37.910
It is actually
those super cavities

00:24:37.910 --> 00:24:43.910
which have enabled the study
of single photon physics.

00:24:43.910 --> 00:24:47.080
Because after all, photons move
away with the speed of light.

00:24:47.080 --> 00:24:50.110
And if you want to observe
a photon in your laboratory,

00:24:50.110 --> 00:24:52.850
it has to bounce around
zillions of times

00:24:52.850 --> 00:24:55.619
in order to have enough
time for the photon

00:24:55.619 --> 00:24:56.785
to do something interesting.

00:25:18.780 --> 00:25:25.110
So sometimes a field at
the frontier of science

00:25:25.110 --> 00:25:31.500
is defined by paradigms.

00:25:31.500 --> 00:25:39.840
If you want to explain
to somebody why

00:25:39.840 --> 00:25:44.020
your field of interest
is cool and exciting,

00:25:44.020 --> 00:25:48.320
you usually do it by picking a
few really exciting examples.

00:25:48.320 --> 00:25:57.220
And I want to show you how,
over the years, it has advanced.

00:25:57.220 --> 00:26:00.320
Definitely in the
'50s and '60s, you

00:26:00.320 --> 00:26:05.730
would have mentioned that we
understand now atomic structure

00:26:05.730 --> 00:26:09.750
of multi-electron atoms.

00:26:09.750 --> 00:26:11.780
Optical pumping just started.

00:26:11.780 --> 00:26:15.735
So these were flagship
developments of AMO science.

00:26:18.310 --> 00:26:20.850
The cool thing to do
in the '60s and '80s

00:26:20.850 --> 00:26:25.380
was, use the new tool, the
laser, applied to atoms

00:26:25.380 --> 00:26:28.740
and do laser spectroscopy.

00:26:28.740 --> 00:26:32.150
Sub-doppler spectroscopy,
sub-natural spectroscopy,

00:26:32.150 --> 00:26:34.050
resolving hyperfine
structure-- wow.

00:26:34.050 --> 00:26:36.400
I mean, this was really
exciting in those days.

00:26:42.660 --> 00:26:46.250
And well, the older
people I have met,

00:26:46.250 --> 00:26:48.790
my teachers, my
thesis adviser, these

00:26:48.790 --> 00:26:51.840
were people who started
their research career

00:26:51.840 --> 00:26:54.100
before the laser was
invented but then,

00:26:54.100 --> 00:26:57.170
as a young researcher,
embraced this new tool

00:26:57.170 --> 00:26:58.870
and helped to
redefine the field.

00:27:02.550 --> 00:27:08.140
Definitely in the '80s and
'90s, the cool pictures

00:27:08.140 --> 00:27:10.910
were those of
magneto-optical traps,

00:27:10.910 --> 00:27:14.280
atoms standing still
and hovering around.

00:27:14.280 --> 00:27:21.590
So the new aspect
where mechanical forces

00:27:21.590 --> 00:27:27.860
of light which led to laser
cooling and trapped atoms.

00:27:30.450 --> 00:27:34.490
In the late '90s, of
course, the excitement

00:27:34.490 --> 00:27:37.280
was about Bose-Einstein
condensation.

00:27:37.280 --> 00:27:40.240
And it was really
Bose-Einstein condensation

00:27:40.240 --> 00:27:46.360
which drove AMO physics
from single atoms, maybe

00:27:46.360 --> 00:27:48.860
two atoms colliding,
to many-body physics.

00:27:53.160 --> 00:27:57.530
It's always easier to
analyze those things

00:27:57.530 --> 00:28:01.440
by looking backward, so if I'm
now getting closer to the past,

00:28:01.440 --> 00:28:03.760
I have to be a little bit vague.

00:28:03.760 --> 00:28:12.010
But in the 2000s, I think hot
topics were ultracold fermions

00:28:12.010 --> 00:28:18.925
and the study of entanglement
and correlations.

00:28:25.290 --> 00:28:31.340
And what is the paradigm
now or in the near future?

00:28:31.340 --> 00:28:34.940
Well, I think you have
to help to define it.

00:28:34.940 --> 00:28:37.070
If you make an
interesting discovery,

00:28:37.070 --> 00:28:40.520
this is what people will be
pointing to and would say,

00:28:40.520 --> 00:28:44.740
this is what now
defines AMO physics.

00:28:44.740 --> 00:28:47.510
Some candidates are,
of course, if there

00:28:47.510 --> 00:28:51.306
is a major breakthrough
in quantum computation--

00:28:51.306 --> 00:28:56.200
let me put question marks here.

00:28:56.200 --> 00:29:01.220
In the field called
atom science,

00:29:01.220 --> 00:29:06.810
we may actually do some progress
towards topological states

00:29:06.810 --> 00:29:10.500
which have different symmetries
and different properties.

00:29:10.500 --> 00:29:16.570
And another emerging frontier
is micro-mechanical oscillators.

00:29:20.480 --> 00:29:22.100
The last couple
of years, we just

00:29:22.100 --> 00:29:24.430
had the breakthrough
for the first time.

00:29:24.430 --> 00:29:28.700
Mechanical objects were cooled
to the absolute ground state.

00:29:28.700 --> 00:29:32.850
So at least for that community
it was, but for many of us,

00:29:32.850 --> 00:29:35.660
Bose-Einstein condensation
was 15 years ago.

00:29:43.420 --> 00:29:44.045
Any questions?

00:29:50.360 --> 00:29:53.810
Well, eventually we have
to talk about this course.

00:30:02.430 --> 00:30:06.845
So I've told you
about, at least,

00:30:06.845 --> 00:30:10.730
a snapshot of where AMO physics
is, how it has developed,

00:30:10.730 --> 00:30:12.510
and on what trajectory it is.

00:30:15.850 --> 00:30:29.830
In this course I want to present
you the concepts behind many

00:30:29.830 --> 00:30:31.900
of the major advances
in the field.

00:30:35.280 --> 00:30:39.390
So over the years, quite often
a topic was added to the course,

00:30:39.390 --> 00:30:41.700
because I felt, hey, that's
getting really exciting,

00:30:41.700 --> 00:30:43.741
that's what people want
to do in research, that's

00:30:43.741 --> 00:30:45.500
what graduate students
want to do here.

00:30:45.500 --> 00:30:49.330
And then the subject was
added and other subjects

00:30:49.330 --> 00:30:51.050
were dropped.

00:30:51.050 --> 00:30:54.010
I know in the '90s, I was
teaching aspects of laser

00:30:54.010 --> 00:30:56.320
cooling, sub recoil
laser cooling,

00:30:56.320 --> 00:30:57.830
which was the latest excitement.

00:31:00.500 --> 00:31:04.580
This year, I may mention
it for 30 seconds.

00:31:04.580 --> 00:31:07.060
So the course has evolved.

00:31:07.060 --> 00:31:10.780
It wants to stay connected to
what is exciting, what is hot,

00:31:10.780 --> 00:31:13.890
and what prepares you for
research at the frontier.

00:31:18.244 --> 00:31:25.820
8.422, the second part
of the two-course cycle

00:31:25.820 --> 00:31:28.460
in the graduate
course in AMO physics,

00:31:28.460 --> 00:31:32.740
is somewhat different,
not radically different,

00:31:32.740 --> 00:31:40.790
but is somewhat different
from part one, from 8.421.

00:31:40.790 --> 00:31:47.190
First of all, 8.421, 8.422
can be taken out of sequence.

00:31:47.190 --> 00:31:51.360
We alternate between
AMO 1 and AMO 2.

00:31:51.360 --> 00:31:54.086
And whenever you
enter MIT, you're

00:31:54.086 --> 00:31:55.460
probably in your
second semester,

00:31:55.460 --> 00:31:57.380
take whatever we offer.

00:31:57.380 --> 00:32:01.966
So I expect-- let me ask you,
who of you has taken AMO 1?

00:32:01.966 --> 00:32:04.340
Yes, statistically, it should
be about half of the class.

00:32:07.150 --> 00:32:11.680
It can be taken out of
sequence because that's

00:32:11.680 --> 00:32:13.260
the way how we've structured it.

00:32:13.260 --> 00:32:16.810
But to give you one
example is, in 8.421

00:32:16.810 --> 00:32:18.940
you really have to learn
about hyperfine structure.

00:32:18.940 --> 00:32:19.903
You have to learn
about atoms, you

00:32:19.903 --> 00:32:21.736
have to learn about
Lamb shift and all that.

00:32:21.736 --> 00:32:25.070
So you have to learn what
all these atomic levels are.

00:32:25.070 --> 00:32:28.250
And here in that course,
in 8.422, I will say,

00:32:28.250 --> 00:32:30.420
here's a two-level system
and then I run with that.

00:32:30.420 --> 00:32:32.290
And we do all sort
of entanglement,

00:32:32.290 --> 00:32:34.660
manipulation of
two-level systems.

00:32:34.660 --> 00:32:38.390
So it helps you if you know
where those two levels come

00:32:38.390 --> 00:32:42.230
from, but you don't really
need the detailed knowledge

00:32:42.230 --> 00:32:44.950
of atomic structure, for
instance, to understand that.

00:32:44.950 --> 00:32:47.780
So this is why the different
parts of the course

00:32:47.780 --> 00:32:52.250
are connected, but in terms of
learning the material, somewhat

00:32:52.250 --> 00:32:53.860
decoupled.

00:32:53.860 --> 00:32:55.860
I've spoken to many
students who said

00:32:55.860 --> 00:32:59.410
there was no problem
in starting with 8.422.

00:32:59.410 --> 00:33:02.980
The only sort of critical
comment I've heard

00:33:02.980 --> 00:33:09.430
is that taking 8.422 first and
then 8.421 is anti-climactic.

00:33:09.430 --> 00:33:11.900
You see all this excitement
in the modern physics,

00:33:11.900 --> 00:33:14.565
and then, eventually, you have
to work on the foundation.

00:33:20.230 --> 00:33:25.050
Prerequisites for this course--
the course announcement

00:33:25.050 --> 00:33:27.500
said 8.05.

00:33:27.500 --> 00:33:31.120
It is actually 8.05 and 8.06.

00:33:31.120 --> 00:33:33.780
The main part of 8.06
which we really need here

00:33:33.780 --> 00:33:37.430
is perturbation theory--
time independent, time

00:33:37.430 --> 00:33:39.690
dependent perturbation
theory, and this is usually

00:33:39.690 --> 00:33:42.570
covered in 8.06.

00:33:42.570 --> 00:33:46.390
However, I've had students who
took the course without 8.06.

00:33:46.390 --> 00:33:48.450
If you're really
determined and want

00:33:48.450 --> 00:33:51.476
to acquire certain
things by self-study,

00:33:51.476 --> 00:33:52.600
you can follow this course.

00:33:56.740 --> 00:34:11.540
So the topics we will
cover include QED.

00:34:14.860 --> 00:34:21.639
I really want to talk about
light-atom interactions

00:34:21.639 --> 00:34:25.070
from first principles.

00:34:25.070 --> 00:34:29.530
Sure, 95% of what
we're doing is just

00:34:29.530 --> 00:34:31.570
done by saying we have
a matrix element, which

00:34:31.570 --> 00:34:33.429
maybe the dipole matrix element.

00:34:33.429 --> 00:34:38.560
But you really have to know what
are the approximations, what

00:34:38.560 --> 00:34:43.159
are the conditions, which lead
to the dipole approximation.

00:34:43.159 --> 00:34:45.710
And I want to do that
from first principles,

00:34:45.710 --> 00:34:47.590
and we do that
starting on Monday.

00:34:50.179 --> 00:35:04.720
So a discussion of light-atom
interaction has two parts.

00:35:04.720 --> 00:35:07.950
One is the simple part--
excitation and stimulated

00:35:07.950 --> 00:35:09.080
emission.

00:35:09.080 --> 00:35:13.420
Because this can be simply
described by a unitary time

00:35:13.420 --> 00:35:19.430
evolution, and you can do
a lot, if not everything,

00:35:19.430 --> 00:35:22.500
by using Schroedinger's
equation.

00:35:22.500 --> 00:35:28.180
Things get much more
complicated and richer

00:35:28.180 --> 00:35:35.000
if you include spontaneous
emission or, more generally,

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:39.060
if you include dissipation.

00:35:39.060 --> 00:35:40.895
Then we talk about open systems.

00:35:44.180 --> 00:35:47.490
And for fundamental reasons,
we need a formulation

00:35:47.490 --> 00:35:50.620
using the density matrix,
a statistical operator,

00:35:50.620 --> 00:35:51.740
and a master equation.

00:35:56.480 --> 00:36:01.740
One major part of the course
is discussion and [INAUDIBLE]

00:36:01.740 --> 00:36:05.470
derivation of the
mechanical forces of light.

00:36:11.870 --> 00:36:15.170
This will include
a discussion of

00:36:15.170 --> 00:36:19.040
important experimental
techniques using

00:36:19.040 --> 00:36:20.830
those mechanical forces.

00:36:20.830 --> 00:36:26.530
So various simple and
sophisticated methods

00:36:26.530 --> 00:36:27.550
of trapping and cooling.

00:36:31.450 --> 00:36:36.820
We will spend some time in not
talking about atoms at all.

00:36:36.820 --> 00:36:42.490
We're just going to talk about
photons, about single photons.

00:36:42.490 --> 00:36:46.150
We want to understand where
the photon nature of light

00:36:46.150 --> 00:36:48.390
makes light very,
very different from

00:36:48.390 --> 00:36:50.360
a classical
electromagnetic wave.

00:36:52.940 --> 00:36:57.510
Also, it's not
the focus, we will

00:36:57.510 --> 00:37:04.080
come across basic building
blocks of quantum information

00:37:04.080 --> 00:37:05.450
science.

00:37:05.450 --> 00:37:08.060
Pretty much when atoms
and photons interact,

00:37:08.060 --> 00:37:10.880
this is a fundamental
quantum gate.

00:37:13.440 --> 00:37:16.070
And we'll talk about
the many-body physics

00:37:16.070 --> 00:37:17.295
off quantum gases.

00:37:23.480 --> 00:37:29.890
So maybe it becomes
clearer what we

00:37:29.890 --> 00:37:35.860
are covering by saying
what we are not covering.

00:37:39.260 --> 00:37:41.820
And this tells you
that there is at least

00:37:41.820 --> 00:37:43.400
some selection of topics.

00:37:43.400 --> 00:37:46.120
It's not that we talk
about everything.

