00:48:40.910 --> 00:48:46.880
And what I now want to use
as an example which clearly

00:48:46.880 --> 00:48:50.470
synthesizes many
aspects of this course

00:48:50.470 --> 00:48:53.000
are atoms in an optical lattice.

00:48:55.670 --> 00:49:06.470
So let me, in the last,
next 20 minutes or so,

00:49:06.470 --> 00:49:12.270
make some connections to
different topics of this course

00:49:12.270 --> 00:49:19.570
by using as a starting point a
concrete, very simple system,

00:49:19.570 --> 00:49:21.680
but very, very
rich and profound,

00:49:21.680 --> 00:49:24.910
and these are atoms
in optical lattice.

00:49:24.910 --> 00:49:28.390
So the situation
I want to use here

00:49:28.390 --> 00:49:34.120
is that you have two laser
beams which interfere.

00:49:34.120 --> 00:49:38.820
And those laser beams form
an optical standing wave.

00:49:43.400 --> 00:49:55.630
So next week we will learn
how this electromagnetic wave

00:49:55.630 --> 00:49:59.350
interacts with atoms.

00:49:59.350 --> 00:50:02.900
So we have to put a few
atoms into the system.

00:50:02.900 --> 00:50:06.460
And we will derive, from
first principles, the QED

00:50:06.460 --> 00:50:14.100
Hamiltonian, which, after a lot
of manipulation and eliminating

00:50:14.100 --> 00:50:22.210
complicated terms, will
be the dipole interaction.

00:50:22.210 --> 00:50:25.380
But of course, each symbol
here is an operator,

00:50:25.380 --> 00:50:27.333
and there's a long
story behind that.

00:50:35.320 --> 00:50:42.280
In about two months, we will
describe light-atom interaction

00:50:42.280 --> 00:50:46.170
with a formalism
which uses a Bloch

00:50:46.170 --> 00:50:50.140
vector and the optical
Bloch equations.

00:50:50.140 --> 00:50:53.650
There is a vector with
three components which

00:50:53.650 --> 00:50:59.120
describes what is the
state the atom is in.

00:50:59.120 --> 00:51:01.670
One component will
tell us if the atom

00:51:01.670 --> 00:51:05.690
is in the upper or
the lower state,

00:51:05.690 --> 00:51:08.970
whereas the other
components tell us

00:51:08.970 --> 00:51:12.290
whether the dipole
moment of the atom

00:51:12.290 --> 00:51:21.360
is in phase or out of
phase with a driving

00:51:21.360 --> 00:51:22.610
electromagnetic field.

00:51:27.600 --> 00:51:40.670
Well, if there is part of
the dipole moment which

00:51:40.670 --> 00:51:46.590
is in phase with a
driving electric field,

00:51:46.590 --> 00:51:51.790
then the suitable
expectation value

00:51:51.790 --> 00:51:55.490
defines a mechanical potential.

00:51:55.490 --> 00:51:58.630
And if the electric
field is a standing wave,

00:51:58.630 --> 00:52:02.635
then we generate, through
light-atom interaction,

00:52:02.635 --> 00:52:05.320
a periodic potential
for the atoms.

00:52:08.960 --> 00:52:13.070
We will learn
everything which we

00:52:13.070 --> 00:52:16.710
have to know about
this potential.

00:52:16.710 --> 00:52:20.500
In a simple case, it is
simply the Rabi frequency

00:52:20.500 --> 00:52:26.860
divided by the detuning of
the electromagnetic wave.

00:52:26.860 --> 00:52:31.430
But we will find
it very interesting

00:52:31.430 --> 00:52:34.490
to look at it from very
different point of view.

00:52:34.490 --> 00:52:35.970
And maybe let me
use this example

00:52:35.970 --> 00:52:40.600
to point out that I'm really
a big friend of explaining

00:52:40.600 --> 00:52:44.910
the same physics from very,
very different perspectives.

00:52:44.910 --> 00:52:48.350
And when we talk about
optical standing waves,

00:52:48.350 --> 00:52:51.300
we will use a picture of
a classical potential,

00:52:51.300 --> 00:52:54.680
like a mechanical potential, and
the atom is just moving around.

00:52:54.680 --> 00:52:57.860
We will use a photon picture
that every time the atom

00:52:57.860 --> 00:53:00.574
feels a force,
photons are involved.

00:53:00.574 --> 00:53:02.490
You don't see them in
the classical potential,

00:53:02.490 --> 00:53:06.020
but photons are behind it,
and ultimately, the forces

00:53:06.020 --> 00:53:09.315
of the classic potential come
from stimulated absorption

00:53:09.315 --> 00:53:10.290
emission of photons.

00:53:12.870 --> 00:53:16.280
I may go down to the
microscopic level.

00:53:16.280 --> 00:53:18.910
And I may ask you, but
in the end, it's an atom,

00:53:18.910 --> 00:53:21.270
but the atom consists
of electrons.

00:53:21.270 --> 00:53:23.630
And the electrons are
simply oscillating

00:53:23.630 --> 00:53:26.850
because it's driven by
the electromagnetic field.

00:53:26.850 --> 00:53:29.560
It's actually something which
most people are not aware of,

00:53:29.560 --> 00:53:32.320
but you can ask
the question now--

00:53:32.320 --> 00:53:38.010
is the force in the optical
lattice on the atom,

00:53:38.010 --> 00:53:40.960
it's ultimately a
force on the electron?

00:53:40.960 --> 00:53:42.885
Well, if you have
a charged particle,

00:53:42.885 --> 00:53:45.890
you can have two kinds of
forces-- an electric force

00:53:45.890 --> 00:53:48.510
or the Lorenz force.

00:53:48.510 --> 00:53:51.020
And I don't know if you
would know the answer,

00:53:51.020 --> 00:53:54.320
but an atom is in
an optical lattice,

00:53:54.320 --> 00:53:57.730
is the force just
the [INAUDIBLE]

00:53:57.730 --> 00:54:00.540
the potential which
the atom experiences,

00:54:00.540 --> 00:54:04.450
is that fundamentally due
to the Coulomb force exerted

00:54:04.450 --> 00:54:06.450
by the electric
field of the light,

00:54:06.450 --> 00:54:09.110
or is it due to the
Lorenz force exerted

00:54:09.110 --> 00:54:10.560
by the magnetic
part of the light?

00:54:13.840 --> 00:54:15.400
Who knows the answer?

00:54:15.400 --> 00:54:17.870
Who doesn't know the answer?

00:54:17.870 --> 00:54:18.970
OK, great.

00:54:18.970 --> 00:54:20.720
I was actually surprised
when I derived it

00:54:20.720 --> 00:54:22.280
a few times for the first time.

00:54:22.280 --> 00:54:24.740
And it's not in the
standard textbooks.

00:54:24.740 --> 00:54:29.270
So anyway, I hope, even for
many of you who know already

00:54:29.270 --> 00:54:31.330
a lot about the
subject, I hope I

00:54:31.330 --> 00:54:36.670
can add other
perspectives for you.

00:54:36.670 --> 00:54:40.340
OK, so what I've
discussed so far

00:54:40.340 --> 00:54:44.470
is that the standing
wave of light

00:54:44.470 --> 00:54:54.330
creates now a periodic
potential for the atom.

00:54:54.330 --> 00:54:57.730
And we will understand it
from many, many different

00:54:57.730 --> 00:55:00.850
perspectives, from the
photon type, quantum optics

00:55:00.850 --> 00:55:03.160
perspective, to the most
classical description.

00:55:05.670 --> 00:55:09.520
So what immediately
comes to my mind

00:55:09.520 --> 00:55:14.120
is that we now want to look at
this periodic potential in two

00:55:14.120 --> 00:55:14.995
different situations.

00:55:19.930 --> 00:55:22.540
We can ask, well,
whenever you have light,

00:55:22.540 --> 00:55:25.350
spontaneous emission
is a possibility.

00:55:25.350 --> 00:55:31.030
And we may ask, what happens
when spontaneous emission

00:55:31.030 --> 00:55:31.910
is not negligible?

00:55:35.330 --> 00:55:37.900
And we discuss
that approximately

00:55:37.900 --> 00:55:40.960
in week nine of the course.

00:55:40.960 --> 00:55:46.090
Then what happens is, an atom
has an excited and a ground

00:55:46.090 --> 00:55:47.410
state.

00:55:47.410 --> 00:55:50.520
And those in the excited
and the ground state,

00:55:50.520 --> 00:55:54.140
do the atoms feel the
periodic potential?

00:55:58.940 --> 00:56:06.240
Well, eventually, we
have to generalize

00:56:06.240 --> 00:56:10.550
the notion of ground and excited
state into [INAUDIBLE] states,

00:56:10.550 --> 00:56:14.000
and I will tell you all
about it in a few weeks.

00:56:14.000 --> 00:56:18.010
But the situation can now be,
when an atom is in the ground

00:56:18.010 --> 00:56:22.570
state, it has to move up
the standing wave potential.

00:56:22.570 --> 00:56:25.200
Then it's getting
excited with a laser.

00:56:25.200 --> 00:56:28.980
It has to move up again the
standing wave potential.

00:56:28.980 --> 00:56:32.380
And then there may be
spontaneous emission.

00:56:32.380 --> 00:56:35.210
So what I'm just describing
here is a situation

00:56:35.210 --> 00:56:39.280
where the atom is mechanically
moving up the potential.

00:56:39.280 --> 00:56:41.630
It's excited at the
top of the potential.

00:56:41.630 --> 00:56:44.040
And it emits when it's
on top of the potential.

00:56:44.040 --> 00:56:47.230
So the atom is doing
mechanical work,

00:56:47.230 --> 00:56:50.950
and this is called
Sisyphus cooling.

00:56:50.950 --> 00:56:57.240
This is the way, this is
one method, one mechanism,

00:56:57.240 --> 00:56:59.760
of laser cooling which
leads to the lowest

00:56:59.760 --> 00:57:03.550
temperatures in the laboratory
before evaporative cooling is

00:57:03.550 --> 00:57:04.600
used.

00:57:04.600 --> 00:57:07.030
So that's some cool
aspect we will come along

00:57:07.030 --> 00:57:09.710
by discussing motion
in a standing wave,

00:57:09.710 --> 00:57:16.340
but taking into account
that photons are emitted

00:57:16.340 --> 00:57:19.570
and really understanding
when and where

00:57:19.570 --> 00:57:22.770
are the photons emitted.

00:57:22.770 --> 00:57:29.290
Well, the second
situation is, of course,

00:57:29.290 --> 00:57:32.455
if spontaneous emission
is completely negligible.

00:57:38.220 --> 00:57:43.470
Then we have a situation
where all what matters

00:57:43.470 --> 00:57:46.830
is the potential,
and we can completely

00:57:46.830 --> 00:57:51.550
forget that it's photons,
it's quantum optics

00:57:51.550 --> 00:57:53.400
which has created
this potential.

00:57:53.400 --> 00:57:56.150
We can simply use a
classical potential

00:57:56.150 --> 00:57:59.710
in our description
in our Hamiltonian.

00:58:02.300 --> 00:58:05.930
Now, again, we have
two limiting cases.

00:58:08.750 --> 00:58:15.340
One case is when this
potential, or optical lattice,

00:58:15.340 --> 00:58:18.630
is really deep.

00:58:18.630 --> 00:58:25.150
Deep means that atoms are
sitting deep in the potential

00:58:25.150 --> 00:58:32.840
and they can oscillate around,
but they cannot jump over

00:58:32.840 --> 00:58:35.810
to the next potential.

00:58:35.810 --> 00:58:42.190
So in this situation, you
would say, well, that's boring.

00:58:42.190 --> 00:58:44.770
Nothing happens, the
atom just stays put.

00:58:44.770 --> 00:58:46.370
But what is boring
for some of you

00:58:46.370 --> 00:58:49.740
is exciting for some
others, because these atoms

00:58:49.740 --> 00:58:52.110
are exquisitely controlled.

00:58:52.110 --> 00:58:56.040
They cannot collide, they cannot
interact with other atoms.

00:58:56.040 --> 00:58:59.360
So these are really the
most ideal situation

00:58:59.360 --> 00:59:01.910
you can imagine for atoms.

00:59:01.910 --> 00:59:06.020
Of course, if you have less
than one atom per site.

00:59:06.020 --> 00:59:12.150
And this is the way how
you want to prepare atoms

00:59:12.150 --> 00:59:16.170
for the most accurate
interrogations.

00:59:16.170 --> 00:59:20.910
And you can build atomic
clocks, optical atomic clocks,

00:59:20.910 --> 00:59:24.040
based on atoms insulated
in such a lattice, which

00:59:24.040 --> 00:59:26.635
approach now 10 to
the minus 17 accuracy.

00:59:32.190 --> 00:59:36.200
Well, if you drive
a clock transition,

00:59:36.200 --> 00:59:39.550
if you take the atom from the
ground to the excited state,

00:59:39.550 --> 00:59:43.420
you may face a situation
I mentioned earlier

00:59:43.420 --> 00:59:46.590
that the periodic potential for
the ground and excited state

00:59:46.590 --> 00:59:47.750
are different.

00:59:47.750 --> 00:59:50.460
And that would actually
interfere with your clock,

00:59:50.460 --> 00:59:53.030
because the clock
frequency depends now

00:59:53.030 --> 00:59:56.470
on what the lattice is
doing to your atoms.

00:59:56.470 --> 01:00:03.360
However, and we discuss
that in week four,

01:00:03.360 --> 01:00:11.860
there are what people
call magic wavelengths,

01:00:11.860 --> 01:00:13.880
where you pick a
certain wavelength

01:00:13.880 --> 01:00:22.750
for your optical lattice where
the periodic potential is

01:00:22.750 --> 01:00:26.780
absolutely the same for
ground and excited state.

01:00:31.210 --> 01:00:36.680
So that means you have,
then, the perfect decoupling

01:00:36.680 --> 01:00:38.650
between the ticking
of the clock,

01:00:38.650 --> 01:00:40.600
the internal
structure of the atom

01:00:40.600 --> 01:00:44.870
and the mechanical motion of
the atoms in the potential.

01:00:44.870 --> 01:00:55.290
And in that situation,
you create a situation

01:00:55.290 --> 01:00:59.270
which has been studied
since [INAUDIBLE], namely

01:00:59.270 --> 01:01:00.270
with trapped ions.

01:01:05.740 --> 01:01:09.855
If you have a single
ion in an ion trap--

01:01:09.855 --> 01:01:13.830
and ion trapping is pursued here
at MIT in Ike Chuang's group--

01:01:13.830 --> 01:01:17.990
you have just a single
object completely isolated.

01:01:17.990 --> 01:01:23.730
And in the form of
the aluminum ion,

01:01:23.730 --> 01:01:28.280
this has just been
demonstrated to be

01:01:28.280 --> 01:01:31.390
the most accurate atomic
clock in the world with 10

01:01:31.390 --> 01:01:34.150
to the minus 17 accuracy.

01:01:34.150 --> 01:01:37.880
So anyway, with
optical lattices,

01:01:37.880 --> 01:01:41.690
avoiding spontaneous emission
using magic wavelengths,

01:01:41.690 --> 01:01:46.120
we can only engineer
with neutral atoms what

01:01:46.120 --> 01:01:48.500
has been available
with trapped ions

01:01:48.500 --> 01:01:51.950
but we can simultaneously
have 10,000 copies

01:01:51.950 --> 01:01:55.350
and look at 10,000 atoms which
are all identical copies,

01:01:55.350 --> 01:01:56.790
identical systems
with each other.

01:01:59.520 --> 01:02:01.590
So you see already
from that example

01:02:01.590 --> 01:02:06.180
that there will be intellectual
overlap and synergy

01:02:06.180 --> 01:02:09.920
between talking about neutral
atoms in optical lattices

01:02:09.920 --> 01:02:15.610
and talking about trapped
ions and how they are cooled

01:02:15.610 --> 01:02:17.510
and how they are manipulated.

01:02:17.510 --> 01:02:20.670
And we'll talk
about trapped ions

01:02:20.670 --> 01:02:22.850
at the end of the
course, sideband cooling

01:02:22.850 --> 01:02:24.550
of trapped ions,
which is week 12.

01:02:30.660 --> 01:02:35.390
OK, so this is the simple
but pristine situation

01:02:35.390 --> 01:02:39.400
that we have a deep lattice.

01:02:39.400 --> 01:02:43.940
The other limit is
now that we have

01:02:43.940 --> 01:02:47.030
a weak, or shallow lattice.

01:02:47.030 --> 01:02:50.980
And the new physics
which now comes into play

01:02:50.980 --> 01:02:55.240
is that atoms can
move around-- they

01:02:55.240 --> 01:02:58.260
can tunnel from side to side.

01:03:01.010 --> 01:03:08.910
So towards the
end of the course,

01:03:08.910 --> 01:03:14.180
I think the last months,
approximately week 10,

01:03:14.180 --> 01:03:17.060
I will give you a short
summary of what some of you

01:03:17.060 --> 01:03:23.410
may have already learned in the
solid state course-- namely,

01:03:23.410 --> 01:03:34.990
band structure of atoms in
optical lattices, Bloch states,

01:03:34.990 --> 01:03:37.960
effective mass, et cetera.

01:03:37.960 --> 01:03:41.870
This has now become
language of atomic physics,

01:03:41.870 --> 01:03:48.280
because there is a very clean
and straightforward realization

01:03:48.280 --> 01:03:51.270
of this physics
using cold atoms.

01:03:54.020 --> 01:03:57.790
What we are mainly interested
in, in our research,

01:03:57.790 --> 01:04:07.890
is when we have atoms which
tunnel in this optical lattice.

01:04:07.890 --> 01:04:12.680
And for bosons, if the
interactions get strong enough,

01:04:12.680 --> 01:04:16.980
the Bose-Einstein
condensate is destroyed

01:04:16.980 --> 01:04:18.450
and what forms is
a Mott insulator.

01:04:21.150 --> 01:04:22.970
This is a phase transition.

01:04:22.970 --> 01:04:26.680
And for fermions,
we have a crossover

01:04:26.680 --> 01:04:28.900
from a metal to a
fermionic Mott insulator.

01:04:32.680 --> 01:04:39.180
And with that, we are already
overlapping conceptually

01:04:39.180 --> 01:04:45.750
with condensed matter physics,
because the Mott insulator

01:04:45.750 --> 01:04:50.470
is a paradigm-- one of these
paradigmatic examples where

01:04:50.470 --> 01:04:53.240
you understand
some deep physics.

01:04:53.240 --> 01:04:56.520
It's a paradigm of
condensed matter physics

01:04:56.520 --> 01:05:02.160
where you have only a
partially-filled band.

01:05:02.160 --> 01:05:05.127
Common sense, or
undergraduate textbooks,

01:05:05.127 --> 01:05:06.710
would say,
partially-filled band, this

01:05:06.710 --> 01:05:08.730
means you've a metal,
you've a conductor.

01:05:08.730 --> 01:05:11.550
But because of the
interactions of the atoms,

01:05:11.550 --> 01:05:13.670
the system is an insulator.

01:05:13.670 --> 01:05:16.360
So this is where, really,
the many-body physics

01:05:16.360 --> 01:05:19.180
profoundly changes the
character of your system.

01:05:24.400 --> 01:05:25.590
Any questions?

01:05:30.090 --> 01:05:35.170
Well then, let me
add one last aspect

01:05:35.170 --> 01:05:42.396
to my introductory example
of optical lattices.

01:05:42.396 --> 01:05:44.770
In a sort of
flyover, I described

01:05:44.770 --> 01:05:47.540
to you what is the
physics we encounter when

01:05:47.540 --> 01:05:49.550
we have an optical
lattice switched on

01:05:49.550 --> 01:05:52.950
and the atoms move around
or they don't move around,

01:05:52.950 --> 01:05:55.150
and both cases are interesting.

01:05:55.150 --> 01:05:57.989
But if you think you've
explored everything, well,

01:05:57.989 --> 01:05:59.780
then you think harder
and say, hey, there's

01:05:59.780 --> 01:06:01.610
another angle we
can get out of it.

01:06:01.610 --> 01:06:05.110
And this is, we can
take the optical lettuce

01:06:05.110 --> 01:06:08.740
and simply pulse it on,
switch it on and off.

01:06:11.380 --> 01:06:14.380
Well, what happens
is, and then it

01:06:14.380 --> 01:06:17.390
becomes a
time-dependent problem.

01:06:17.390 --> 01:06:22.910
It becomes something where
we can shape and control

01:06:22.910 --> 01:06:26.690
the wave function of atoms
in time-dependent way.

01:06:26.690 --> 01:06:28.240
Let me give you one example.

01:06:28.240 --> 01:06:30.980
If we start with
very cold atoms-- can

01:06:30.980 --> 01:06:36.920
be a Bose-Einstein condensate--
and then, for a short time,

01:06:36.920 --> 01:06:45.010
we switch on the
lattice, afterwards, we

01:06:45.010 --> 01:06:51.140
observe that we have still
some atoms at zero momentum.

01:06:51.140 --> 01:06:57.680
But now we have atoms which
have a momentum transfer of plus

01:06:57.680 --> 01:07:01.660
minus 2 h bar k.

01:07:01.660 --> 01:07:05.630
You can understand
that-- and this again

01:07:05.630 --> 01:07:08.200
exemplifies that we want
to look at the physics

01:07:08.200 --> 01:07:10.440
from different
angles-- this can be

01:07:10.440 --> 01:07:18.020
described that you have
an two-photon transition

01:07:18.020 --> 01:07:22.710
from the ground state with
zero momentum to the ground

01:07:22.710 --> 01:07:27.520
state with two-photon recoil.

01:07:27.520 --> 01:07:30.590
So you can understand it
in the photon picture.

01:07:30.590 --> 01:07:34.010
But you can also
understand it by saying

01:07:34.010 --> 01:07:39.460
you have some matter
waves which are now

01:07:39.460 --> 01:07:43.380
exposed to a periodic potential.

01:07:43.380 --> 01:07:47.250
And you simply ask
what happens to waves

01:07:47.250 --> 01:07:48.870
in a periodic potential?

01:07:48.870 --> 01:07:52.660
Well, that's the same what
happens to optical waves

01:07:52.660 --> 01:07:55.295
when they encounter
a grading, and that's

01:07:55.295 --> 01:07:56.420
the physics of diffraction.

01:08:00.760 --> 01:08:04.650
So in a nutshell,
this happens when

01:08:04.650 --> 01:08:16.080
we use a pulse on an
optical potential.

01:08:16.080 --> 01:08:18.740
And let me now finish
by telling you that,

01:08:18.740 --> 01:08:24.319
again, in this situation,
we discover the ambiguity

01:08:24.319 --> 01:08:28.350
or the two-sidedness of a lot of
things we do in atomic physics.

01:08:28.350 --> 01:08:30.979
I've mentioned to you
that the same experiment,

01:08:30.979 --> 01:08:34.390
the same experimental setup,
cold atoms in optical lattice--

01:08:34.390 --> 01:08:37.100
you turn up the lattice and
you have the world's best

01:08:37.100 --> 01:08:40.170
atomic clock, atoms just
isolated from each other.

01:08:40.170 --> 01:08:41.582
You turn down the
lattice and you

01:08:41.582 --> 01:08:44.020
have an interesting condensed
matter physics system.

01:08:44.020 --> 01:08:47.990
Let me just show you that
the same two-sidedness

01:08:47.990 --> 01:08:50.910
of atomic physics-- precision
and pristine control

01:08:50.910 --> 01:08:52.920
and interesting
many-body physics--

01:08:52.920 --> 01:08:56.810
happens when you pulse
on optical lattices.

01:08:56.810 --> 01:09:02.990
So one application of
those optical lettuces

01:09:02.990 --> 01:09:05.590
is atom optics.

01:09:05.590 --> 01:09:13.800
You have atoms and when they
encounter an optical lattice,

01:09:13.800 --> 01:09:20.574
some atoms will just continue,
will not be diffracted.

01:09:26.590 --> 01:09:28.899
They have zero momentums.

01:09:28.899 --> 01:09:34.310
Others are diffracted with
a transverse momentum.

01:09:34.310 --> 01:09:39.979
You can then expose the
atoms to a second zone

01:09:39.979 --> 01:09:44.740
where, eventually,
momentum is transferred,

01:09:44.740 --> 01:09:48.189
and then the atoms
come back together.

01:09:48.189 --> 01:09:52.069
So what we have here is an
atom interferometer where

01:09:52.069 --> 01:09:56.105
atomic matter waves first
go through a beam splitter,

01:09:56.105 --> 01:09:59.894
are reflected back towards each
other, all by photon transfer,

01:09:59.894 --> 01:10:01.060
and then they're recombined.

01:10:07.130 --> 01:10:15.940
So this pulsed optical lattice
acts as a beam splitter.

01:10:15.940 --> 01:10:24.880
It is the way how, today,
the most precise atom

01:10:24.880 --> 01:10:27.760
interferometers are built.

01:10:27.760 --> 01:10:31.060
And this is used for
precision measurement,

01:10:31.060 --> 01:10:36.510
for measurement of inertial
forces, gravity, rotation,

01:10:36.510 --> 01:10:45.760
acceleration, and it is used
for navigation and accurate

01:10:45.760 --> 01:10:49.450
observation of the changes
of the gravitational field

01:10:49.450 --> 01:10:52.010
of the Earth.

01:10:52.010 --> 01:10:55.940
Since we just had a talk by
Holger Mueller from Berkeley

01:10:55.940 --> 01:10:58.350
day before yesterday
over at Harvard,

01:10:58.350 --> 01:11:01.980
he talked about the combination
of atom interferometer

01:11:01.980 --> 01:11:04.360
and frequency combs,
another development--

01:11:04.360 --> 01:11:05.940
let me just mention that.

01:11:05.940 --> 01:11:09.700
If you derive those
laser frequencies

01:11:09.700 --> 01:11:13.160
from an optical frequency comb,
and with an optical frequency

01:11:13.160 --> 01:11:15.740
comb you can pretty much
count the frequencies.

01:11:15.740 --> 01:11:20.440
So this laser is mode,
I don't know-- 100,000

01:11:20.440 --> 01:11:22.720
or whatever you are in the comb.

01:11:22.720 --> 01:11:26.570
By doing that, by combining
it, you can actually

01:11:26.570 --> 01:11:32.000
build an atomic clock
where-- let me just say,

01:11:32.000 --> 01:11:36.070
plus combs-- can
give an atomic clock

01:11:36.070 --> 01:11:42.940
which is called the Compton
clock because the frequency is

01:11:42.940 --> 01:11:47.930
now given by the rest
mass of the atom,

01:11:47.930 --> 01:11:51.180
but divided by a
big integer number.

01:11:51.180 --> 01:11:56.190
So using completely unrelated
developments in AMO science

01:11:56.190 --> 01:11:59.810
which I've mentioned, the
optical frequency comb,

01:11:59.810 --> 01:12:03.145
combining it with the physics
of a pulse standing wave,

01:12:03.145 --> 01:12:07.030
you now have an atomic clock
which is directly related

01:12:07.030 --> 01:12:08.525
to the energy of the rest mass.

01:12:16.780 --> 01:12:24.950
But finally, if you pulse
on an optical standing wave

01:12:24.950 --> 01:12:29.200
and your object are
not individual atoms,

01:12:29.200 --> 01:12:31.960
non-interacting
atoms, your object

01:12:31.960 --> 01:12:37.050
is the Bose-Einstein condensate
or atoms which strongly

01:12:37.050 --> 01:12:40.440
interact, then you're
not transferring

01:12:40.440 --> 01:12:43.130
recoil to individual
atoms, you're

01:12:43.130 --> 01:12:48.750
transferring momentum to a
complicated many-body system.

01:12:48.750 --> 01:12:53.940
And this means what
we are measuring

01:12:53.940 --> 01:12:56.420
is the dynamic structure factor.

01:13:02.702 --> 01:13:04.660
If you have atoms, you
want to do spectroscopy,

01:13:04.660 --> 01:13:06.970
you want to know what
energy levels are there,

01:13:06.970 --> 01:13:08.470
and then you know your atom.

01:13:08.470 --> 01:13:10.530
If you have a
strongly-interacting system,

01:13:10.530 --> 01:13:13.330
you also want to know what
energy levels are there.

01:13:13.330 --> 01:13:16.390
But each energy level
in a homogeneous system

01:13:16.390 --> 01:13:18.460
or in a periodic
potential is associated

01:13:18.460 --> 01:13:20.500
with momentum and
quasi-momentum.

01:13:20.500 --> 01:13:23.700
So in other words, if you have
a more complicated system,

01:13:23.700 --> 01:13:27.080
you want to figure out what are
the possible states in terms

01:13:27.080 --> 01:13:29.680
of momentum and energy.

01:13:29.680 --> 01:13:32.610
And the optical standing wave,
the pulsed optical standing

01:13:32.610 --> 01:13:35.810
wave is the way how we
impart momentum and energy

01:13:35.810 --> 01:13:38.330
to a system.

01:13:38.330 --> 01:13:41.800
What I actually just
told you is a story

01:13:41.800 --> 01:13:44.430
in my own research career.

01:13:44.430 --> 01:13:46.190
I was a post-doc
with Dave Pritchard.

01:13:46.190 --> 01:13:48.010
He had trained at
MIT in the '90s

01:13:48.010 --> 01:13:50.070
by a pioneer in laser cooling.

01:13:50.070 --> 01:13:52.110
And when we had
Bose-Einstein condensates

01:13:52.110 --> 01:13:56.790
in the late '90s, Professor
Pritchard and myself,

01:13:56.790 --> 01:13:57.969
we teamed up.

01:13:57.969 --> 01:13:59.885
I was the expert on
Bose-Einstein condensation

01:13:59.885 --> 01:14:03.910
and he was the expert
on atom interferometry.

01:14:03.910 --> 01:14:06.460
So just by sort of
exploring things,

01:14:06.460 --> 01:14:08.630
we took Bose-Einstein
condensates

01:14:08.630 --> 01:14:10.940
and we pulsed on
a standing wave.

01:14:10.940 --> 01:14:14.790
What was on our mind was, hey,
let's build an interferometer.

01:14:14.790 --> 01:14:19.410
But I'm more of a
many-body physics person.

01:14:19.410 --> 01:14:21.775
I suddenly said,
yes, but if we now

01:14:21.775 --> 01:14:24.950
change the momentum and the
frequency of this standing

01:14:24.950 --> 01:14:26.400
wave, what happens?

01:14:26.400 --> 01:14:28.245
And I suddenly
realized that this

01:14:28.245 --> 01:14:31.720
is a way to measure properties
of a Bose-Einstein condensate

01:14:31.720 --> 01:14:34.440
in a way which hadn't
been done before.

01:14:34.440 --> 01:14:36.790
So I realized--
and this is maybe

01:14:36.790 --> 01:14:38.530
the last thing I want
to tell you today--

01:14:38.530 --> 01:14:41.150
I realized in my own
research and my collaboration

01:14:41.150 --> 01:14:43.750
with Dave Pritchard, that
we'd built an experiment,

01:14:43.750 --> 01:14:47.460
and we just turned one
knob at our experiment,

01:14:47.460 --> 01:14:50.300
and the following day
we were no longer doing

01:14:50.300 --> 01:14:54.690
atomic interferometry, we
were doing many-body physics.

01:14:54.690 --> 01:14:57.670
So this is, I think, what
makes our field exciting.

01:14:57.670 --> 01:15:03.890
We are using the tools, the
precision, and the control

01:15:03.890 --> 01:15:07.590
of atomic physics,
which leads to the most

01:15:07.590 --> 01:15:11.677
accurate atomic
clocks in the world--

01:15:11.677 --> 01:15:14.010
atomic clocks, which are the
most accurate in the world.

01:15:14.010 --> 01:15:17.520
And we are using those tools to
do entanglement and many-body

01:15:17.520 --> 01:15:18.130
physics.

01:15:18.130 --> 01:15:21.800
And I think it's just a
compelling combination.

01:15:21.800 --> 01:15:23.550
Anyway, that's an
appetizer, that's

01:15:23.550 --> 01:15:26.006
an outlook over the semester.

